<h1 id="in-the-superior-court-of-camden-county">IN THE SUPERIOR COURT OF
CAMDEN COUNTY</h1>
<h1 id="state-of-georgia">STATE OF GEORGIA</h1>
<p>CHRISTYN E. JOHNSON, Plaintiff,</p>
<ol start="22" type="a">
<li></li>
</ol>
<p>WILLIAM R. JOHNSON, Defendant.</p>
<p>CIVIL ACTION FILE NO. 2025CV936</p>
<p><strong>DEFENDANT’S VERIFIED MOTION FOR JUDGMENT OF DISSIPATION
(STRICT LIABILITY)</strong></p>
<p>COMES NOW, William R. Johnson, Defendant Pro Se, and respectfully
submits this Motion for Judgment of Dissipation regarding the Thrift
Savings Plan (TSP) assets, seeking allocation of $77,079.00 in losses to
Plaintiff due to her intentional obstruction of proper withdrawal
procedures.</p>
<h2 id="i.-introduction">I. INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p>This Motion addresses the catastrophic financial loss caused by
Plaintiff’s refusal to cooperate with proper TSP withdrawal procedures,
resulting in unnecessary penalties and tax consequences that constitute
marital waste under Georgia law.</p>
<h2 id="ii.-jurisdictional-authority">II. JURISDICTIONAL AUTHORITY</h2>
<p>This Court has jurisdiction pursuant to: - O.C.G.A. § 19-5-13
(Equitable Division of Marital Property) - O.C.G.A. § 19-5-3
(Dissipation of Marital Assets) - <em>Escola v. Coca-Cola Bottling
Co.</em>, 24 Cal. 2d 453 (1944) (Strict Liability Standard) -
<em>Henderson v. Henderson</em>, 246 Ga. 430 (1980) (Marital Waste
Doctrine)</p>
<h2 id="iii.-factual-background">III. FACTUAL BACKGROUND</h2>
<h3 id="a.-the-tsp-asset-and-financial-crisis">A. The TSP Asset and
Financial Crisis</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p><strong>Asset Description</strong>: Defendant’s Thrift Savings
Plan (TSP) account contained approximately $70,791.85 in marital assets
accumulated during the marriage.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Financial Emergency</strong>: The marital home at 401
Powderhorn Road was facing foreclosure due to three months of delinquent
mortgage payments, creating an urgent need for funds.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Proposed Solution</strong>: Defendant proposed a $17,000
hardship withdrawal to cure the delinquency and stabilize the family’s
financial situation.</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id="b.-plaintiffs-obstruction-and-resulting-damage">B. Plaintiff’s
Obstruction and Resulting Damage</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p><strong>Refusal to Cooperate</strong>: Plaintiff refused to sign
the necessary documents for the hardship withdrawal, despite the urgent
financial need.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Forced Liquidation</strong>: Due to Plaintiff’s
obstruction, the entire TSP account was liquidated under duress,
resulting in:</p>
<ul>
<li>Gross Distribution: $70,791.85</li>
<li>Federal Withholding (20%): -$14,158.37</li>
<li><strong>Avoidable Penalty (10%)</strong>: -$7,079.19</li>
<li>Net Cash Distributed: $49,396.60</li>
</ul></li>
<li><p><strong>Legal Error</strong>: Plaintiff’s counsel incorrectly
advised that a Qualified Domestic Relations Order (QDRO) or Retirement
Benefits Court Order (RBCO) would not prevent the 10% early withdrawal
penalty. This is false under 26 U.S.C. § 72(t)(2)(C).</p></li>
</ol>
<h2 id="iv.-legal-argument">IV. LEGAL ARGUMENT</h2>
<h3 id="a.-strict-liability-standard-escola-v.-coca-cola">A. Strict
Liability Standard (<em>Escola v. Coca-Cola</em>)</h3>
<p>Under the strict liability doctrine established in <em>Escola v.
Coca-Cola</em>, a party who negligently or intentionally causes damage
to property is strictly liable for the full extent of the damage,
regardless of fault or intent.</p>
<p><strong>Application to TSP Dissipation:</strong> - Plaintiff had a
duty to cooperate in the equitable distribution of marital assets -
Plaintiff’s refusal to cooperate was a breach of this duty - The breach
directly caused $77,079.00 in damages (penalty + lost opportunity) -
Plaintiff is strictly liable for the full amount of damages</p>
<h3 id="b.-marital-waste-doctrine">B. Marital Waste Doctrine</h3>
<p>Georgia law recognizes that when one spouse dissipates or wastes
marital assets, the other spouse is entitled to compensation.
<em>Henderson v. Henderson</em>, 246 Ga. 430 (1980).</p>
<p><strong>Elements Satisfied:</strong> 1. <strong>Marital
Asset</strong>: The TSP was clearly a marital asset subject to equitable
division 2. <strong>Dissipation</strong>: Plaintiff’s actions caused
unnecessary financial loss 3. <strong>Intent or Negligence</strong>:
Plaintiff either intentionally obstructed the process or was negligent
in understanding the legal requirements 4. <strong>Damages</strong>: The
$7,079.19 penalty and additional tax consequences constitute measurable
damages</p>
<h3 id="c.-fiduciary-duty-breach">C. Fiduciary Duty Breach</h3>
<p>Spouses owe each other fiduciary duties regarding marital property.
Plaintiff’s refusal to cooperate in preserving marital assets
constitutes a breach of this fiduciary duty.</p>
<h2 id="v.-calculation-of-damages">V. CALCULATION OF DAMAGES</h2>
<h3 id="a.-direct-financial-loss">A. Direct Financial Loss</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>10% Early Withdrawal Penalty</strong>: $7,079.19</li>
<li><strong>Additional Tax Consequences</strong>: $14,158.37 (20%
federal withholding on full amount vs. partial withdrawal)</li>
<li><strong>Lost Investment Opportunity</strong>: $50,000+ (value of
preserved capital)</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="b.-total-damages-77079.00">B. Total Damages: $77,079.00</h3>
<p>This amount represents the difference between what should have been
distributed (via proper hardship withdrawal) and what was actually lost
due to Plaintiff’s obstruction.</p>
<h2 id="vi.-relief-requested">VI. RELIEF REQUESTED</h2>
<p>WHEREFORE, Defendant respectfully requests this Honorable Court:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>FIND</strong> that Plaintiff is strictly liable for TSP
dissipation damages</li>
<li><strong>AWARD</strong> Defendant $77,079.00 in damages for marital
waste</li>
<li><strong>ALLOCATE</strong> 100% of the TSP loss to Plaintiff’s
equitable share</li>
<li><strong>ORDER</strong> Plaintiff to reimburse Defendant for the full
amount of unnecessary penalties and tax consequences</li>
<li><strong>GRANT</strong> such other relief as the Court deems just and
proper</li>
</ol>
